ll Towns in Andalusia, Spain -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEconomic arrangements of Romanies are complexly related to their social position. The authors of this volume explore these complexities, including how economic exchanges forge key social relationships of gender and ethnicity, how economic opportunities are constructed and seized, and how economic success and failure are transformed into attributes of social persons. They explore how, despite — or perhaps because of — their unstable and ambiguous position within the market economy, shared today with a growing number of people facing precarity and informalisation, Roma and Gypsy communities continuously re-create more or less viable economic strategies. The ethnographically based chapters share accounts of socially and economically vulnerable populations that face their situation with self-determination and creativity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszEurope. 0aCommunity lifezEurope. 0aEuropexEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aEuropexEthnic relations. 0aMarginality, SocialxEconomic aspectszEurope. 0aRomanieszEuropexEconomic conditionsy21st century. 0aRomanieszEuropexSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aValuesxSocial aspectszEurope. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAcedo, Sara Sama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrazzabeni, Micol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrazzabeni, Micol, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCunha, Manuela Ivone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDurst, Judit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 